Working with Nested and Repeated Fields

Open BigQuery Console

  1. In the Google Cloud Console, select Navigation menu > BigQuery.

The Welcome to BigQuery in the Cloud Console message box opens. This message box provides a link to the quickstart guide and lists UI updates.

  1. Click Done.

Open the IRS Public Dataset inside BigQuery:

https://console.cloud.google.com/bigquery?project=data-to-insights&page=irs_990.irs_990_ein

In the BigQuery console, select data-to-insights > irs_990 > irs_990_repeated.

You are given a reporting table that has nested and repeated rows. Each ein has it's name and corresponding expense and revenue accounts repeated. You will practice querying repeated rows through the use of UNNEST( ).

Skim the below schema and note the repeated fields.

Step 1

Preview the Contents of the table by running the following query in the Query Editor (or using the Web UI to find and Preview).

#standardSQL SELECT * FROM `data-to-insights.irs_990.irs_990_repeated` LIMIT 10

The results should look similar to the below:

Using BigQuery with Standard SQL will automatically flatten the array content into rows (as shown above) compared to Legacy SQL will return an error stating you need to explicitly flatten.

Step 2

Attempt to filter for all the Legal expenses by running the below query.

#standardSQL SELECT * FROM `data-to-insights.irs_990.irs_990_repeated` WHERE expense_struct.type = 'Legal' LIMIT 10

Step 3

Confirm the error:

Error: Cannot access field type on a value with type ARRAY<STRUCT<type STRING, amount INT64>>

We need to find another way to access those array elements.

Step 4

Find the top 10 nonprofits that spent the most on legal expenses in the table.

As a start, complete the below query by adding in the appropriate UNNEST( ) and WHERE Clause filter on the expense type for Legal'.

Hint: UNNEST( ) typically follows the FROM much like a JOIN and should enclose a STRUCT.

#standardSQL # Expenses by Category for each EIN SELECT ein, expense FROM `data-to-insights.irs_990.irs_990_repeated` n CROSS JOIN expense_struct AS expense ORDER BY expense.amount DESC LIMIT 10

Step 5

Compare against the below solution:

#standardSQL # Expenses by Category for each EIN SELECT ein, expense FROM `data-to-insights.irs_990.irs_990_repeated` n CROSS JOIN UNNEST(n.expense_struct) AS expense WHERE expense.type = 'Legal' ORDER BY expense.amount DESC LIMIT 10

Step 6

Run the Query.

Step 7

Confirm the Result:

Note: The CROSS JOIN and UNNEST( ) can be shorthanded as shown below. The CROSS JOIN becomes a comma and the UNNEST( ) is optional as BigQuery assumes you want to unnest the n.expense_struct.

#standardSQL # Expenses by Category for each EIN SELECT ein, expense FROM `data-to-insights.irs_990.irs_990_repeated` n, n.expense_struct AS expense WHERE expense.type = 'Legal' ORDER BY expense.amount DESC LIMIT 10

Congratulations!

You have completed the second part of the Nested and Repeated Fields lab.

Learning Review

  • Arrays contain a set of values in a single field

  • Use UNNEST() to work with data in arrays

  • STRUCTs are containers for data

  • BigQuery Repeated Fields are Arrays of Structs

  • BigQuery tables with repeated fields are essentially pre-joined tables with significant performance benefits

References

  • Standard SQL and Legacy SQL handle repeated fields in very different ways. Refer to the migration guide to see key differences in syntax.
  • Standard SQL Working with Arrays
